ived for three centuries or so along the upper ridges of the Yolmo Valley in north central Nepal.It was clear through their many conversations that both individuals perceived themselves as nearing death, and both were quite willing to share their thoughts about death and dying. The difference between the two was remarkable, however, in that Ghang Lama's life had been dominated by motifs of vision, whereas Kisang Omu's accounts of her life largely involved a "theatre of voices." Desjarlais offers a fresh and readable inquiry into how people's ways of sensing the world contribute to how they live and how they recollect their lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBuddhistszNepalvBiography. 0aDeathxReligious aspectsxBuddhism. 0aHelambu Sherpa (Nepalese people)xReligion. 0aLamaszNepalvBiography. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  abiographical profiles.  abiographical.  abuddhist priests.  adeath and dying.  adeath experience.  aethnographers.  aethnographic studies.  agerontology.  ahuman struggles.  ainterviews.  alife and death.  alife histories.  alife journey.  alife stories.  anepal.  anonfiction biography.  aphysical senses.  areligious figures.  asensory experiences.  asociology.  aspiritual.  asubjective experience.  atibetan buddhists.  atouching.  avision.  ayolmo buddhists.  ayolmo elders.  ayolmo valley.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023587840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093674440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520936744423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520936744/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEB